text:
I don't like Modi or the BJP at all.  But many of the people I met in India, regardless of their religion -- Hindu, Muslim, Sikh, Catholic, Zoroastrian, etc. -- touched me greatly with not just their acceptance of others' religions, but their embracing of them, while still having their own deep spirituality.  
(One Sindhi family who had to leave Pakistan after the Partition because they were Hindu did not express bitterness at their plight, and they still welcomed me and took care of me even though I have an Islamic background.  The matriarch actually followed a lot of the Sufis from Pakistan.)  
It isn't something you see frequently in the West.  
Because of what I saw, and the history I knew, it always kind of saddened me that the Subcontinent was not united; I always looked at the violent political division at being a legacy of colonial strategy, which operated on Divide and Conquer in order to gain power.  
But under Modi/the BJP, India seems to adopting only the worse habits of the West.  
Really unfortunate.

By Iqbal Latif

Power, until tested, is revered. But when displayed unnecessarily, it exposes its own limits. That is the essence of deterrence: a strong leader must never swing the stick â€” unless certain that the blow will land precisely.

Modi had a big stick â€” the benefit of ambiguity, the fear of overwhelming force, and the rising global stature of India. But he used it â€” not for a calculated strike, but merely for a show of bravado. And in doing so, he revealed the hollowness of that power.

Now, the enemy no longer fears the stick.
Now, the world has seen that Indian airpower can be checked.
And Pakistan â€” the target of Modiâ€™s strategic designs â€” has not emerged weakened, but awakened.
This was not just a strategic failure; it was a historic moment â€” when India lost its dominance not through defeat, but through overreach.

This was not a mere skirmish. It was an attempted redraw of the map of power and perception. But Indiaâ€™s strategy â€” intended to assert dominance â€” only ended up exposing its limitations. The Indian Air Force, long considered superior, was tested â€” and stopped. The stick meant to break Pakistan shattered mid-air.

Modiâ€™s deeper plan was clear:
	1.	Provoke Pakistan into a nuclear overreaction,
	2.	Isolate it on the global stage,
	3.	Destroy its credibility.

But Pakistan didnâ€™t blink.
It stood its ground with restraint, precision, and strategy.
Backed by Chinese ISR, radar, and missile networks, Pakistan turned potential defeat into regional balance.
	â€¢	The myth of Rafale jets evaporated.
	â€¢	INS Vikrant quietly withdrew.
	â€¢	And Indiaâ€™s psychological dominance â€” its most potent weapon â€” was lost.

It was a trial of strength. And India showed its hand, shattering the illusion of superiority.
The Indian Air Force, once seen as invincible, has now been measured, weighed â€” and checked.
The entire framework of conventional superiority â€” built for a day like this â€” collapsed before the public eye.
	1.	The myth is broken.
	2.	Psychological dominance is gone.
	3.	And the dream of â€œAkhand Bharatâ€ â€” wrapped in nationalist slogans â€” has washed away.

Pakistanâ€™s Rendezvous with Destiny: From Brink to Brilliance

Last night will be remembered not for what happened â€” but for what didnâ€™t:
	â€¢	The â€œfallâ€ of Islamabad,
	â€¢	The â€œdestructionâ€ of Karachi Port,
	â€¢	The â€œarrestâ€ of General Asim Munir â€”
All were final attempts by Indian media to stage a theatrical illusion of victory â€” a drama of psychological conquest.

But it failed. And in that failure, a new reality emerged.

Today, as Modi looks north, he sees a restored alliance â€” Pakistan and China, closer than ever before.
This was Pakistanâ€™s rendezvous with its history â€” an existential moment handled with dignity and precision.
The very jets India once mocked as â€œflying metal tubesâ€ have redefined deterrence.

Pakistan showcased the most integrated defensive strategy and real-time coordination in modern South Asian military history.

And now, as Indiaâ€™s pride has been humbled, a new era begins â€” less of arrogance, more of humility.
The Arab world will no longer see Modi through the same lens.
Nor will Trump or the West.
Because they have seen the truth:
	1.	Pakistan stands at the crossroads of Karakoram, the Silk Road, Wagah, Khyber, and Torkham.
	2.	It holds not just geography, but the key to regional stability for 2.8 billion people.
	3.	The strategic map has shifted â€” and so has the worldâ€™s perspective.

Strategic Forecast: Modiâ€™s Miscalculation and the Dawn of a New Balance

What began as a show of strength has become a textbook example of strategic error.
Modiâ€™s goal was clear:
	1.	Assert dominance, humiliate Pakistan swiftly, and cement Indiaâ€™s regional supremacy.
The plan relied on Indian Air Force superiority, Rafale jets, INS Vikrant, satellite intelligence, and political swagger.
	2.	In Modiâ€™s mind, the war was 99% won â€” only one final strike remained.

But the illusion shattered the moment Indian jets entered contested airspace.

Pakistan Air Force didnâ€™t just have radars â€” it had eyes in space:

As India moved its airpower to forward â€œTigerâ€ bases â€” Pakistan was watching.

And it can be stopped.

Modiâ€™s dream â€” to â€œeraseâ€ Pakistan, divide it, dry its rivers, destroy its cities â€”

To those asking why Afghans support India ğŸ‡®ğŸ‡³ over Pakistan ğŸ‡µğŸ‡° in times of conflict, let me make this clear: our issue is not with the people of Pakistan, but with the Pakistani military and political establishment which for decades has acted as an enemy to the Afghan nation, despite pretending to be a â€œMuslim neighbor.â€

Letâ€™s look at history and facts:
	1.	Sanctuary for destruction: After 9/11, it was Pakistan that gave military bases to the United States to launch airstrikes on Afghanistan, leading to the death of over 1 million innocent Afghans. While Afghans were burning under bombs, Pakistan was earning dollars in return.
	2.	Safe haven for terrorism: The Pakistani military openly harbored and supported the Taliban and other extremist groups who killed our teachers, our doctors, our children, and destroyed our progress. Even Osama bin Laden was found in Abbottabad, not Kabul.
	3.	Strategic depth policy: Pakistan has treated Afghanistan as its â€œbackyardâ€ under its evil â€œstrategic depthâ€ doctrine, creating instability and chaos so that Afghanistan could never stand on its feet.
	4.	Violation of Islamic brotherhood: Islam teaches us not to betray your neighbor and not to support oppressors. The Qurâ€™an says: â€œDo not incline toward the oppressors, lest you be touched by the Fireâ€¦â€ (Surah Hud, 11:113). What Pakistan did to Afghanistan is nothing but betrayal and oppressionâ€”from supporting the Taliban to sending spies, bombs, and fake peace.
	5.	Durand Line oppression: They are still fencing the illegal Durand Line, dividing Afghan families, and killing innocent Afghans with cross-border shellingâ€”even as we extend the hand of peace.

So yes, many Afghans support Indiaâ€”not because India is perfect or because we are against Muslims, but because India has never sent suicide bombers to our mosques, never funded terrorists against us, and never tried to enslave our nation through proxy war.

text: Bangladesh has valid, historically documented reasons to remain wary of forging close ties with Pakistan, stemming from the systematic genocide committed by the Pakistani military during the 1971 Liberation War. According to declassified documents, international journalists, and the Hamoodur Rahman Commission Report, the Pakistani Army and its collaborators were responsible for the mass killing of an estimated 300,000 to 3 million people, including students, intellectuals, scientists, and civilians, and the violation of approximately 200,000 to 400,000 women, as reported by the UN and the Bangladeshi government. Targeted massacres took place in places like Dhaka University, where intellectuals and students were brutally executed. On March 25, 1971, during "Operation Searchlight," the Pakistani military initiated a campaign to silence Bengali demands for autonomy by launching one of the most violent crackdowns in South Asian history. Entire villages were burned, women were taken to camps and subjected to inhumane abuse, and newborns were murdered in front of their families. These acts were not collateral damage of war, they were calculated. The Pakistani state explicitly denied Bengali identity, suppressed the Bengali language, and sought to maintain dominance by terrorizing the population into submission. The victims were predominantly Muslim, revealing that religious identity was no shield against ethnic and linguistic persecution. To this day, Pakistan has not officially apologized for the atrocities of 1971. Many war criminals were protected or later integrated into Pakistani politics. There is a persistent lack of remorse, justice, or reconciliation from the Pakistani state, which Bangladeshis view as a refusal to acknowledge the blood on its hands. Therefore, any political or social attempt to normalize relations with Pakistan without accountability undermines the memory of the victims, the sacrifices of the Mukti Bahini, and the very foundation of Bangladeshi independence. Friendship cannot be built on denial, silence, or historical amnesia. It must be earned through truth, justice, and repentance, none of which Pakistan has offered.

text:
Â @Argus_The_DarkAngelÂ  Thatâ€™s a sweet sentimentâ€”but letâ€™s come back down to Earth for a moment.

If by â€œrevelationâ€ you mean a handful of emotional online posts, thatâ€™s not a diplomatic shiftâ€”itâ€™s a Twitter mood swing. Bangladeshâ€“Pakistan relations are still diplomatically cold, and no amount of wishful slogans changes that. Bangladesh hasnâ€™t forgotten the 1971 genocide, when over 3 million Bangladeshis were killed and thousands of women raped by the Pakistani military. To this day, Pakistan has never officially apologized, and Bangladeshis still commemorate the Liberation War every year with pride and pain. That history is not erased by a few online â€œbrotherâ€ comments.

Economically, diplomatically, and strategically, Bangladesh is closely aligned with India, and that hasnâ€™t changed. You canâ€™t wish away deep economic integration, joint border coordination, and regional security partnerships with a paragraph of sentiment. Thereâ€™s no â€œuprising.â€ Thereâ€™s no strategic pivot. Thereâ€™s no evidence of Bangladesh cutting ties with India, rejecting trade, or signing security agreements with Pakistan. Thatâ€™s not how statecraft works.

You say â€œIndia canâ€™t control anything about Bangladeshâ€â€”but nobody said it does. Bangladesh is a sovereign nation. But sovereignty doesnâ€™t mean aligning yourself with a collapsing state apparatus like Pakistanâ€™s, which is lurching from one economic crisis to another, and where even basic governance is under strain. Aligning with Pakistan â€œwithout hesitationâ€ isnâ€™t loyaltyâ€”itâ€™s strategic blindness.

Brotherhood is beautiful when itâ€™s grounded in reality. But slogans donâ€™t feed people, secure borders, or build futures. Bangladeshâ€™s prosperity has come from independence, economic growth, regional stability, and smart diplomacyâ€”not emotional alliances with militaries who once turned Dhaka into a graveyard.

So yes, may you have a great day tooâ€”but preferably with your eyes open.

The idea of a â€œGreater Israelâ€ â€” meaning Israel expanding to control all territory from the Nile to the Euphrates â€” is not the official policy of the State of Israel, nor is it supported by most Israelis or the Israeli government.

Hereâ€™s a breakdown:

1. The â€œGreater Israelâ€ Myth:
	â€¢	Antisemites and anti-Zionists often claim that Israel seeks to conquer large parts of the Middle East, citing a misinterpretation of biblical texts or extremist fringe views.
	â€¢	In reality, the vast majority of Israeli Jews, including mainstream politicians, do not support such an idea.
	â€¢	The Israeli Declaration of Independence supports peaceful coexistence and never mentions â€œexpanding borders.â€

2. Who does support it?
	â€¢	Only fringe ideological groups (like some religious extremists or Kahanist-type figures) dream of â€œGreater Israel.â€
	â€¢	These groups have no real power in Israeli politics, and their views are rejected by most Israeli Jews, including secular, religious-Zionist, and centrist communities.

3. Reality:
	â€¢	Israel has actually given up land for peace (like Sinai to Egypt, Gaza disengagement in 2005).
	â€¢	Its real strategic interest is security, not imperial expansion.
	â€¢	Even Netanyahu and Likud, considered right-wing, have never made â€œGreater Israelâ€ an official platform.

4. Why this lie is pushed:
	â€¢	To demonize Israel and compare it to colonial empires.
	â€¢	It feeds pan-Arabist and Islamist narratives that paint Israel as a regional aggressor rather than a state defending its existence.

So no â€” Israel does not seek a â€œGreater Israelâ€, and saying so is propaganda, not fact.

text:
3:45 ,The word "Bharat" comes from ancient times â€” long before the names "India" or any colonial term existed. It is named after King Bharata, a mighty emperor mentioned in the Mahabharata and ancient Hindu texts like the Puranas.

He was a legendary ruler who united many lands under Dharma, strength, and knowledge. Because of his legacy, the land came to be known as â€œBharatvarshaâ€ â€” the realm of Bharata.

This name is not just a label â€” it's a symbol of civilizational pride. It reflects our own identity, rooted in Sanatan dharma, culture, and history. Even our Constitution begins with:
â€œIndia, that is Bharatâ€¦â€

So Bharat is not just a name â€” itâ€™s who we are. A nation born from its own soil, not from foreign definitions.
author: @INGOBRO

text:
2:03, Akhand Bharat is not just an idea â€” it's a historical truth and a rightful demand.
The regions now called Pakistan, Bangladesh, Afghanistan, Nepal, Sri Lanka, and even the Maldives were once part of ancient Bharat, united under powerful Hindu empires and bound by the same civilization, language roots, and culture.

Over centuries, this land was invaded, divided, and stolen â€” first by foreign Islamic invaders, then by British colonizers, and finally broken through the forced Partition of 1947, which tore our civilization apart. Indians never chose this division â€” it was imposed.

Thatâ€™s why the call for Akhand Bharat is not about aggression â€” itâ€™s about reclaiming what was ours, what was taken from us through bloodshed, deceit, and foreign politics. Itâ€™s a demand born from memory, pain, and truth. Our land wasnâ€™t divided naturally â€” it was broken.

Akhand Bharat lives in our hearts because our civilization was one â€” and no amount of false borders can erase that.

1:40 , He Said India Occupied Kasmir, 
Who occupied Kashmir first?

In 1947, after India and Pakistan became independent, the ruler of Kashmir (a Hindu king of a Muslim-majority state) wanted to stay independent.

But Pakistan sent tribal fighters to invade Kashmir on October 22, 1947. This was the first act of occupation.

In response, the Maharaja asked India for help and legally joined India by signing the Instrument of Accession on October 26, 1947. Indian troops then pushed back the invaders.

So, Pakistan occupied parts of Kashmir first, and India entered only after a legal request by the ruler.

It's misleading to present a few tweets from Indian users as the voice of an entire nation. Incidents like the 26/11 attacks, the Kargil War, the Parliament attack, and the Uri strikeâ€”where countless innocent lives were lost, including Muslimsâ€”are stark reminders of the terrorism India has endured. Most of these attacks were carried out by Pakistan-based terrorist groups, yet India consistently chose diplomatic responses for years.

However, when diplomacy failed to stop the bloodshed, targeted counter-terrorism operations were necessary and justified. These were not random acts of aggression but precise strikes on known terror camps.

If fairness is the goal, then why ignore what the Pakistani military did to fellow Muslims in Bangladesh in 1971? Or the ongoing human rights violations against the Baloch people? India, home to more Muslims than Pakistan, remains a diverse and democratic society where Muslims hold key political and social roles. Even prominent leaders like Asaduddin Owaisi have openly condemned Pakistanâ€™s actions.

Selective outrage and narratives driven by diaspora biases do a disservice to the truth and to the principles of balanced journalism.

I just want to know the opinion of  muslims living in countries other than pakistan about me and my problem. What would you do in this situation? .
I am an extremely introvert and innocent guy living in pakistan. I actually never had a chance to talk to a single classfellow ( boys) or any male due to my introvertness.. so i never made any friends ever. You could imagine how difficult it would be to survive this way. I never talked to my father .He is no more in this world now. I have not got any cousins or males around me . I never went out of the house alone ever and i know nothing about basic things. I look like a kid but my age is 30 plus now. So i actually never went to mosque to offer eid or friday prayers too ever as it is also outside the house. I never went to the barber for my haircut.  Now it was my strong wish to go and offer eid prayers but i cant go alone its not in my hands. So i wanted a friend from my country who could accompany me to mosque and guide me . See i dont go outside stays indoors ..what could i do? I messaged bearded men considering them pious on facebook i messaged alot of men asking for this small innocent help i wanted to set things right as soon as possible. But to my surprise all the men , boys , men older to me did nor bother to understand or help or even show some respect and sympathy. Majority of them had to say : nobody could help you start going on a walk. When i already clarified i take my mother with for my haircut what is the point of advising foolish suggestions. And few said you may go to psychologist i made them clear that i am mentally perfect belong to a decent family its just because i never had the chance to interact with any male. My father never took me anywhere. He was himself an introvert probably.  Now pakistani muslims disappointed me alot. I was never expecting them the way they turned out to be. I can be considered like a foreigner living in pakistan unaware and ignorant of things. 
Now i am hopeless 
I just want to know from muslims living in other countries if they would have helped me if i was a part of their country? 
I am teary eyed. i want to know what other muslims fellows would do in this situation . Would your reaction be the same as pakistanis or different. Would you add me in your lives and accompany me to offer prayers which is my strongest wish.

To those asking why Afghans support India ğŸ‡®ğŸ‡³ over Pakistan ğŸ‡µğŸ‡° in times of conflict, let me make this clear: our issue is not with the people of Pakistan, but with the Pakistani military and political establishment which for decades has acted as an enemy to the Afghan nation, despite pretending to be a â€œMuslim neighbor.â€

Letâ€™s look at history and facts:
	1.	Sanctuary for destruction: After 9/11, it was Pakistan that gave military bases to the United States to launch airstrikes on Afghanistan, leading to the death of over 1 million innocent Afghans. While Afghans were burning under bombs, Pakistan was earning dollars in return.
	2.	Safe haven for terrorism: The Pakistani military openly harbored and supported the Taliban and other extremist groups who killed our teachers, our doctors, our children, and destroyed our progress. Even Osama bin Laden was found in Abbottabad, not Kabul.
	3.	Strategic depth policy: Pakistan has treated Afghanistan as its â€œbackyardâ€ under its evil â€œstrategic depthâ€ doctrine, creating instability and chaos so that Afghanistan could never stand on its feet.
	4.	Violation of Islamic brotherhood: Islam teaches us not to betray your neighbor and not to support oppressors. The Qurâ€™an says: â€œDo not incline toward the oppressors, lest you be touched by the Fireâ€¦â€ (Surah Hud, 11:113). text:
As an Afghan, it's important to understand why some Afghans choose to support India â€” not necessarily out of loyalty or admiration, but because of the long and troubled history with Pakistan. For decades, Pakistan has maintained a hostile stance toward Afghanistan, from political interference to carrying out airstrikes on Afghan soil. Given that history, it's understandable that some Afghans would align themselves with countries that oppose Pakistan. However, many people overlook the reality of Indiaâ€™s rising nationalism and how it affects its own Muslim population. The treatment of Muslims in India under its current political leadership is deeply concerning and shouldnâ€™t be ignored or excused.

Personally, I believe in standing with our fellow Muslim neighbors and promoting unity rather than division. That said, supporting our neighbors doesn't mean blindly backing governments â€” especially not the Pakistani government, which has its own issues and history of harming Afghanistan. There's a clear difference between supporting people and supporting regimes.

text:
The ideas of Akhand Bharat and the Greater Israel project are both expansionist-nationalist visions rooted in historical, religious, and cultural claims. While these concepts are not official state policies (and are often denied by governments), they are promoted by ideological groups tied to Hindutva in India and Zionism in Israel, especially in their far-right expressions.

Hereâ€™s a breakdown of the similarities between Akhand Bharat and Greater Israel:

1. Ideological Roots in Religious Nationalism

Akhand Bharat is a Hindutva vision of a united â€œundivided Indiaâ€ that includes modern-day India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nepal, Bhutan, Afghanistan, Sri Lanka, and Tibet.

Greater Israel is a vision drawn from biblical and religious Zionism, claiming land from the Nile to the Euphrates, which could include parts of Lebanon, Syria, Jordan, Iraq, Egypt, and the Palestinian territories.

Similarity: Both envision a revival of a mythologized ancient or religious homeland, to restore national or religious glory.

2. Revisionist Historical Narratives

Akhand Bharat claims that the Indian subcontinent was once a unified Hindu civilization before foreign (especially Muslim and British) invasions.

Greater Israel draws on biblical claims of the land promised to the Israelites by God.

Similarity: Both rely on mythological or ancient historical narratives to legitimize modern political ideologies.

3. Ethnic and Religious Exclusivism

Hindutva envisions India as a Hindu-first nation, with other religions tolerated only if they accept Hindu cultural dominance.

Zionism, especially in its extreme forms, sees Israel as a Jewish homeland, with increasing calls to exclude or subjugate Palestinians.

Similarity: Both ideologies, at their extremes, support ethnoreligious homogeneity and view minorities as demographic or ideological threats.

4. Justification of Settlements and Occupation

Zionists have built Jewish settlements in the West Bank, considered illegal under international law, to â€œreclaimâ€ ancestral lands.

Hindutva groups support demographic and legal changes in Kashmir (post-Article 370) and the Northeast to â€œintegrateâ€ them into Hindu India.

Similarity: Strategic settlement and demographic engineering to change the character of contested or minority regions.

5. Role of Militant Ideologies

Akhand Bharat is promoted by the RSS and Sangh Parivar, which operate grassroots and paramilitary networks.

Greater Israel has been pushed by settler movements, Kahanist factions, and right-wing Zionist parties.

Similarity: Both are driven by ideologically hardline, often violent groups operating outside formal politics, but with close ties to ruling parties.

6. Political Denial vs. Ideological Reality

Indian leaders often distance themselves from Akhand Bharat publicly, but imagery (like murals in Parliament) and rhetoric suggest otherwise.

Israeli governments officially reject Greater Israel, but settlement expansion and annexation policies align with it in practice.

Similarity: Both concepts are denied diplomatically but promoted ideologically, often through education, propaganda, or symbolism.

7. Perception of Civilizational Conflict

Akhand Bharat portrays Hindus as under siege from centuries of Muslim and colonial rule.

Greater Israel frames Jewish survival as dependent on dominance in a hostile Arab world.

Similarity: Both see themselves as civilizations under existential threat, justifying territorial expansion as self-defense or revival.

8. Diaspora Support

Hindu nationalist groups in the U.S., U.K., and Canada fund and promote the Akhand Bharat idea.

Pro-Zionist lobbies and Christian evangelicals support Greater Israel in the U.S. and Europe.

Similarity: Both visions receive significant ideological and financial backing from diasporas.

Conclusion

Akhand Bharat and the Greater Israel project are two ideological visions rooted in religious nationalism, territorial expansion, and historical revisionism. While not formal state policies, they deeply influence domestic politics, foreign policy postures, and attitudes toward minorities.

They represent a broader global trend of ethno-nationalist expansionism, which challenges secularism, pluralism, and international norms â€” with real consequences for peace and stability in their respective regions.
